rawContent:
Full transcript:

“One common mistake that founders make early on is they hire people who are domain experts and are good at listening to the founder and their vision, but don't necessarily each have independently good judgment. 

Now, why would you impose that additional bar of having good judgment on every single team member? It doesn't necessarily seem rational. It's hard to get it in a limited market and pool of people. And aren't you, the founder, running the show anyway?

Early on, this doesn't seem like a problem. You have three, four, five, six people. As a founder, you understand the product and the company. You make all the important decisions. All you need are people who work hard, understand their space, and can do their job. And things are fine.

But then there comes a point when it dawns upon the founder, almost with horror, that they don't fully understand the company anymore. They don't understand the product fully anymore. Maybe they don't understand the finances anymore. Maybe they don't understand the legal complexity anymore. In any case, the problem has become too large for any one person to hold in their head. And even if they could hold it in their head, there's just too many moving parts. There aren't enough hours in the day. There are too many decisions to be made, consequential decisions.

So at this point, what you realize is that you have actually outsourced the development and the judgment of the company to the first 10 or 20 hires you've made. And why the first 10 or 20? Why not beyond? Because those first 10 or 20 will be doing all the hiring after that. Yes, you have a screen, you have a veto, but at the end of the day, the DNA of the company is set by the initial people that you hired. Their judgment percolates out to the new hires. Their decisions ripple through the code base and through the product. Their mindset is evident in all the documents and the customer service and the reactions. 

In that sense, Vinod Khosla was absolutely right. The team you build is the company you build, and the early team you build is really the company that you build. It's very important that all the early people that you hire actually have independently good judgment, and none of them are just cogs in a machine.”

“Isaac Asimov should get full credit for having thought through the AI alignment problem a long time ago.

Like any great sci-fi author, he anticipated what was going to happen 70 to 100 years down the line. And he thought through many of the issues and he came up with the famous three laws of robotics.

And just as a reminder, the three laws were, first, a robot can't harm a human or through inaction allow a human to come to harm. Second, that a robot should obey humans. And third, that the robot was allowed self-preservation.

And these cover some of the big debates going on in AI today. The first one being, are robots going to end us all? The second one being, should robots listen to humans and where do they rank relative to humans? The third one being, robot rights and robot survival.

Asimov laid them out similarly to how we treat animals. So animals, for example, are around to the extent that they help humans or make us feel better and protect and defend and feed and all those things for us. Secondly, animals are outranked by humans. Even the highest ranking animal is essentially outranked by the lowest ranking human within any given society or culture. And then third, there are animal rights, but they're kind of trodden upon by the first two. So these laws were in order of importance.

But just like any three wishes made to a genie, it turned out that even with these three very simple laws, you ended up with lots and lots of problems.

Firstly, of course, there are parts of the laws that can always come in conflict with each other. Consider the first law. A robot cannot harm a human, nor through inaction can it allow a human to come to harm. Even this can conflict in many situations.

It's basically the trolley problem times a million in your head.

Anytime you have a dual mandate, you're going to have contradictions. For example, the Federal Reserve has a dual mandate of price stability and full employment and is constantly vacillating between the two. The SEC has the dual mandate of investor protection and capital formation, but it's easier to destroy and stop than it is to create and build, so it focuses much more on investor protection and much less on capital formation.

So dual mandates themselves fail. Then of course, there’re all the definitional games you can play. For example, what is a robot? If it doesn't know it's a robot, does it have to follow the laws? What is a human? If you define some people as human and others are subhuman, then you have no obligation towards them. What is knowing even mean? What if it's a distributed network and every single bit thinks it's doing something for good, but taken together, it's evil or harmful? This is how mob mentality and mob justice work, after all.

Asimov had a lot of fun writing a lot of stories about this, and eventually he even added a fourth law, or as he called it, a zeroth law, where a robot can't even harm humanity, or allow humanity to come to harm through inaction. So he was closing another loophole there, but the loopholes are of course infinite. Even in such a small logical system, you have infinite loopholes.

At its core, the three laws of robotics had an assumption that every robot that was built would have these laws put into their brain. But that assumes that humans in the first place were aligned on what to do. And the core problem here is that you cannot have an aligned AI that is built by unaligned humans. And humans are unaligned because they're creative and free creatures. And not all of them are ever going to agree on how to practice mathematics and write software code.

You're not going to get all the competing AI builders in the Western world, let alone the Chinese, the Russians, and the Indians and so on and so forth, to agree on how to train and build AIs, especially as these models become easier and easier to use...”

“Isaac Asimov should get full credit for having thought through the AI alignment problem a long time ago.

Like any great sci-fi author, he anticipated what was going to happen 70 to 100 years down the line. And he thought through many of the issues and he came up with the famous three laws of robotics.

And just as a reminder, the three laws were, first, a robot can't harm a human or through inaction allow a human to come to harm. Second, that a robot should obey humans. And third, that the robot was allowed self-preservation.

And these cover some of the big debates going on in AI today. The first one being, are robots going to end us all? The second one being, should robots listen to humans and where do they rank relative to humans? The third one being, robot rights and robot survival.

Asimov laid them out similarly to how we treat animals. So animals, for example, are around to the extent that they help humans or make us feel better and protect and defend and feed and all those things for us. Secondly, animals are outranked by humans. Even the highest ranking animal is essentially outranked by the lowest ranking human within any given society or culture. And then third, there are animal rights, but they're kind of trodden upon by the first two. So these laws were in order of importance.

But just like any three wishes made to a genie, it turned out that even with these three very simple laws, you ended up with lots and lots of problems.

Firstly, of course, there are parts of the laws that can always come in conflict with each other. Consider the first law. A robot cannot harm a human, nor through inaction can it allow a human to come to harm. Even this can conflict in many situations.

It's basically the trolley problem times a million in your head.

Anytime you have a dual mandate, you're going to have contradictions. For example, the Federal Reserve has a dual mandate of price stability and full employment and is constantly vacillating between the two. The SEC has the dual mandate of investor protection and capital formation, but it's easier to destroy and stop than it is to create and build, so it focuses much more on investor protection and much less on capital formation.

So dual mandates themselves fail. Then of course, there’re all the definitional games you can play. For example, what is a robot? If it doesn't know it's a robot, does it have to follow the laws? What is a human? If you define some people as human and others are subhuman, then you have no obligation towards them. What is knowing even mean? What if it's a distributed network and every single bit thinks it's doing something for good, but taken together, it's evil or harmful? This is how mob mentality and mob justice work, after all.

Asimov had a lot of fun writing a lot of stories about this, and eventually he even added a fourth law, or as he called it, a zeroth law, where a robot can't even harm humanity, or allow humanity to come to harm through inaction. So he was closing another loophole there, but the loopholes are of course infinite. Even in such a small logical system, you have infinite loopholes.

At its core, the three laws of robotics had an assumption that every robot that was built would have these laws put into their brain. But that assumes that humans in the first place were aligned on what to do. And the core problem here is that you cannot have an aligned AI that is built by unaligned humans. And humans are unaligned because they're creative and free creatures. And not all of them are ever going to agree on how to practice mathematics and write software code.

You're not going to get all the competing AI builders in the Western world, let alone the Chinese, the Russians, and the Indians and so on and so forth, to agree on how to train and build AIs, especially as these models become easier and easier to use...”

In the future, we will also process other intermediate lithium feedstocks, including those from recycled batteries & manufacturing scrap.

Tesla exists to accelerate the transition to sustainable energy.

Impact Report 2022 → https://t.co/xZBOkoRNUo

—

2022 Highlights

Last year, our customers avoided releasing about 13.4 million metric tons of CO2e into our atmosphere 🌎

Tesla vehicle emissions are significantly lower vs ICE vehicles. This will continue to improve as the grid gets cleaner, while the carbon impact of ICE vehicles remains the same every year.

After 17 years of driving—the average life of a vehicle in the US—a single Tesla will avoid almost 55 tons of CO2e.

Also, the Supercharger network continues to be 100% renewable. This was achieved via onsite resources & annual renewable matching.

user.rawDescription: Electric vehicles, giant batteries & solar

rawContent:
Each Gigafactory we build is more efficient than the last, reducing our vehicles' carbon footprint further.

This includes improving factory layouts, covering roof space with solar panels & leveraging AI to improve how we use energy.

We also reduced water use in vehicle manufacturing by 15% year over year & currently use less water per vehicle than almost any ICE carmaker.

—

We support responsible mining & refining.

Specifically:

- We source directly from mining & refining companies. Avoiding the middleman enables more transparent & easily traceable supply chain data.

- We use external mining initiatives & expect suppliers to undergo independent audits.

In addition, vertical integration & regionalization help us have more control over supply.

None of our batteries go to landfills—at the end of their usable life, we recycle them to build brand-new battery packs.

—

Product affordability is fundamental to our mission.

The more products we sell, the more we move in the needle in favor of a sustainable future. Model 3 is the first EV to be priced on-par with ICE vehicle equivalents.

Tesla vehicles are engineered to be the safest in the world.

By collecting anonymous data from 4M+ vehicles in our fleet & replicating real-world accidents, we’re able to make current & future vehicles even safer.

In 2022, a Tesla with Autopilot engaged experienced 0.18 accidents per million miles driven, while the US average was more than 8x higher.
